I think he oversimplifies mahayana as describing the goal as seeking
an "underlying unity."  At least in Zen, I have not heard any such
emphasis on a "one is all" type thinking, even in teachings on non-
duality.  In fact it sounds like a comparative religion undergrad's
interpretation of Mahayana.   He's gotten it confused with Hinduism.

In fact I once heard Daido Roshi adamantly exclaim "one is NOT all."
To speak of some such abstraction, as some such thing as an
"underlying unity" is to create another kind of polarity.  The
teachings of nonduality are still about disengatement and detachment,
"release from the all" or any concept of "all."

Like I said before.  The truth of the difference between mahayana and
theravada is nothing more to me than a matter of emphasis.  There is
plenty of precedent for non-duality in the Pali canon in discussions
of higher Jhanas and in discussions of awakening, but a term for "non-
duality" simply doesn't appear.  Theravada is a prescriptive practice,
a cure for ending suffering by ending the ignorance that prevents
awakening.  Mahayana is the study of awakening in and of itself.

Submitted for your disapproval... :)

-DaveK
