In zen accounts there is some talk of no-separation.
Perhaps seeing without the sense of a seer, a dropping
of the subject object split.  This is very common even in
ordinary perception under concentration, like reading,
doing sports, even viewing TV.  The subject object split
usually only comes up when 'self' feels threatened or when
natural concentration (or fascination) fails, or when one
attempts to make 'sense' of things by thinking about it.

This may be about the advice of zen masters to 'become the pain',
or the heat or the cold.  Enter in by concentration (as perfected
by meditation) to disperse the subject-object dichotomy and
the necessary difficulties that always must follow a self against
the world.

There are many intellectual arguments by the Buddha to support
no-self.  But primarily no-self is an experience, not an idea.
No-separation seems to be a factor of awakening.

This isn't about passivity.  There is action but no actor.
The sensation of acting is only in the 'understanding'
of a self in the world.  A mind-made problem.

Unity or multiplicity is just one idea or the other.
No idea can transcend the rational dichotomies.
