What you have to be careful of is turning a practice into a
philosophy.  "Become the pain" is a skillful means, but if it leads
you to actually conclude intellectually that you and pain are the
same, then you've introduced a new deluded notion rather than get rid
of an old one.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; There are many intellectual arguments by the Buddha to support
&gt; no-self.  But primarily no-self is an experience, not an idea.
&gt; No-separation seems to be a factor of awakening.
">

Not-self is a teaching that talks about the way one creates suffering
through self identification.  It is not a statement about the
existence of a self.

The Buddha never ever, ever, ever, ever, ever, ever, ever, ever, ever,
ever, ever, ever, ever, ever, ever, ever, ever, ever, said that there
was no self.  He never said there was a self.  He taught that one of
the ways we create suffering is through the idea "I am my body, I am
my feeling...perception..fabrication...conciousness."

To say "there is no self, there is only unity" is to turn a practice
into a philosophy.  There are a helluvalotta Buddhists out there
making this mistake

