I would say, Peter, that this is your terminology for that state or
experience of reality as it really is.  It is not the only way to
describe the awakened state, and it is not a way that I would prefer,
because, as I have told you in the past, that is a kind of terminology
that smacks of intellectual understanding rather than a direct
description of what is.  "no separation of subject and object" probably
describes to you what awakening is like, but it is full of concepts.
Both "subject" and "object" are concepts, so you have to envision them,
then erase them.  To me terms like "no experience of separate self" or
"a state in which you are able to just be and everything is obvious
without any doubt about what to do" or "a state of equanimity and
non-attachment" etc. etc. are more descriptive of the reality of
awakening.  "non duality of subject and object" seems much more abstract
and more removed from a real experience in the moment.

is this because you are intellectual by nature and like to express
yourself in concepts?  Or is it because your awakening is very much
centered in your head and is a product of sorting out thoughts about
reality until you discovered one that puts it all into an essential
form?  I don't know, but I do think that "non duality of subject and
object" may be a good starting point for a description of awakening
realization, but not in itself a real description of anything that can
be easily grasped.

Furthermore, it seems like your certainty that this is the *one most
correct way* to describe the awakened state and that this is the one
property that characterizes it, rather than seeing it as one way to
describe a state that cannot be encapsulated by any particular word or
concept, casts some doubt on the universality and actuality of what you
are describing.  It seems that you are more intent on the correct
concept than on the actuality of what is experienced in awakening.

Robert

