&gt; Buddhism. The ultimate measure of awakening is realization itself, not what
&gt; anyone ever said about it
">

The Buddha did not spend a lot of time talking about awakening in and
of itself.  I think that when he spoke of it he was trying to motivate
people to practice, but otherwise did not like to discuss it that
much.

I don't think anybody described Buddhism better than the Buddha, but
Buddhism is not all about "enlightenment or bust."  Keep in mind that
he also taught to people he knew were not going to awaken in this
lifetime.  From his perspective he was putting people in a better
position to awaken in future lifetimes, or at the very least he was
helping them live in a more harmonized way.  I am well aware that I
could die tomorrow never having awakened to my true nature but I do
not regret any of the practice I have done.

-DaveK
